column169: Clean Harbors was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 1ft-by-1ft area and 2ft-by-2ft area of asphalt and a 10ft-by-3ft area of the trailer floor. They estimated that one (1) gallon of material was released most likely due to a forklift puncturing one (1) 55-gallon metal drum. Clean Harbors personnel inspected all 24 drums on the trailer and found only one (1) drum was affected. The damaged 55-gallon metal drum was contained in one (1) 85-gallon metal drum. Contractor personnel deployed granular absorbents to the affected areas and containerized them into one (1) 55-gallon metal drum. The generated waste was staged onsite and will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

Ariana Lopez with CURA was contacted for remediation on straight time.

column169: The leaking container was picked up by Veolia from a customer on 4/2/25 and transporter to the Veolia 10 Day In-Transit facility located at 3100 Hedley Street, Philadelphia, PA 19137. The container was offloaded with other containers and placed on another transport vehicle the afternoon of 4/2/25. The following day, the container was inspected and was not observed to be leaking. On 4/4/25 during a routine inspection of the site, the container was determined to be leaking as a small wet area was observed around the circumference of the bottom of the container. The container was placed in a salvage drum, and the area decontaminated. The leak was caused most likely by potential damage to the container or a leaking seam in the plastic.
column170: The incident is being reviewed and will be included as part of a weekly update for review by facility personnel. Retraining on DOT compliance occurred with personnel on 4/9/25 and 4/10/25.

On 4/3/2025 at approximately 1330 hours, Dangerous Goods Administration received notification of undeclared dangerous goods.  The shipment consisted of 2 fiberboard boxes, each contained multiple bottles of perfume.   AWB# 772715499316 had 22 bottles of perfume and AWB 772787929150 had 19 bottles of perfume.  Customs intercepted the shipment for further investigation, which confirmed the presence of the perfume.  Neither shipment was prepared in accordance with IATA Regulations, as it did not display the required markings, labeling, packaging, or paperwork.  Customs has requested that the shipments be destroyed.

column169: On April 7, 2025, at 1847, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar Inway personnel in Conroe, TX regarding the release of FLP MC-130 Conc. Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of 330 gallons of FLP MC-130 Conc. (UN1993, 3, III) from (1) 330-gallon poly tote onto the trailer floor and soil. The release was reportedly due to a load shift during transit, impacting the trailer floor and a 30’ x 50’ area of soil surrounding the trailer. No drains or waterways were impacted by the release. The trailer floor was cleaned up with absorbents and the proper PPE. The top layer of impacted soil was removed, then the harder layer underneath was secured for future excavation. 200 gallons of product were recovered from the ground and placed in a tote for potential recycling. The impacted absorbents and removed soil were containerized in (1) roll-off container which was taken offsite by the contractor for proper disposal along with the empty 330-gallon tote and recovered 200 gallons of product.

column169: XPO-Logistics contacted ERTS regarding a punctured leaking poly tote containing hazardous product, Barquat MB-50. A contractor dispatched and observed an estimated 140-gallon release onto the wooden trailer floor, the concrete beneath the trailer, the asphalt parking lot, and the soil. The trailer floor was impacted in a 20’ x 8.5’ area and the concrete beneath the trailer, asphalt, and soil were impacted in a 100’ x 75’ area. The contractor neutralized the release and applied oil dry. A vac truck extracted approximately 2,700-gallons of impacted rainwater and containerized it into one vac box. Three 55-gallon DF’s containing the cut-up tote, impacted oil dry, and impacted PPE were also generated. ERTS will coordinate disposal of the vac box. XPO will manage the drum waste created from the response. No storm-drains or waterways were involved in this incident.

The generated waste will remain onsite for Dayton Freight’s contracted hazardous waste vendor to coordinate disposal.

column169: On April 14, 2025, one (1) 5-gallon pail of UN3109 was punctured and released approximately three (3) cups of product to the dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from GrayMar Environmental Services (GES) to remediate the site. The crew identified the one (1) damaged 5-gallon jug of product, which was placed into its own 55-gallon vented poly drum for waste. The release had been cleaned by terminal personnel, and the jug of product had been patched and plugged. The spent absorbents were placed into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum that was placed into the terminal's dumpster. Crews inspected the dumpster and found that all impacted absorbents were successfully containerized in the one  (1) 55-gallon drum and had not released to the rest of the dumpster, so crews removed the 55-gallon drum. The impacted absorbents were transferred into one (1) new 55-gallon, vented poly drum, and the damaged drum was cut up with hand tools for waste. Crews utilized absorbent pads and cleaning agents to wipe down the impacted dock floor. One (1) 55-gallon vented poly drum of any spent absorbents, cleanup debris, and the cut-up drum was staged alongside the one (1) 55-gallon drum that contained the one (1) impacted jug.

column169: XPO-Logistics contacted ERTS regarding a leaking 55-gallon metal drum containing hazardous product, Leaded Race Fuel. A contractor dispatched and observed an estimated 55-gallons released onto the entire wooden trailer floor, the asphalt beneath the trailer in a 60’x10’ area, and a drain (catch basin) as a result of a forklift puncture. The contractor cleaned up the release using a vac truck and oil dry. One 85-gallon DF containing the empty damaged drum was generated for waste disposal along with three 55-gallon DM’s containing impacted absorbents, and 2,800-gallons of impacted water inside of the vac truck. XPO will manage the waste drums created from the response and ERTS will coordinate disposal of the vac truck liquids at a local third-party disposal site. No waterways or soil were involved in this incident.

XPO-Logistics contacted ERTS regarding damaged leaking jerricans containing, Peraside (Organic Peroxide) and 05-pails with damaged lids containing, Sodium Hypochlorite. A contractor dispatched and observed an estimated 0.5-gallon release of hazardous product, Peraside (Organic Peroxide) onto the concrete dock floor in a 4’ x 2’ area as a result of a forklift puncture. Additionally, the contractor identified four 05-pails of Sodium Hypochlorite with broken lids. The Sodium Hypochlorite did not release, therefore there was no impact area. The contractor generated one 55-gallon DF containing two loose-packed jerricans of Peraside (Organic Peroxide) for waste disposal. The impacted debris and PPE from that clean-up was containerized and wetted inside of a separate 55-gallon DF for waste disposal. Two 55-gallon DF’s containing the four loose-packed 05-pails of Sodium Hypochlorite were generated for waste disposal. XPO will manage all waste created from the response. No storm-drains, waterways, or soil were involved in this incident.
